The '''Wopkaimin''' are a small [[indigenous people|aboriginal tribe]] that lives in the remote [[Star Mountains]] in western [[Papua New Guinea]] in what is known as the [[Fly River|Fly River socio-ecological region]]. The tribe speaks [[Faiwol language|Faiwol]]. The [[Ok Tedi Mine]], the third largest open pit [[copper]] and [[gold]] [[mining|mine]] in the world is located in their traditional territory.<ref name=GoldMountain>{{cite journal|title=A Sacred Mountain of Gold: The Creation of a Mining Resource Frontier in Papua New Guinea|journal=The Journal of Pacific History|date=December 1994|volume=29|issue=2|pages=203–221|jstor=25169228|author=David Hyndman|publisher=Taylor & Francis, Ltd.|doi=10.1080/00223349408572772}}</ref>  Before the coming of the mine with construction starting in 1981 the Wopkaimin lived in a [[subsistence economy]]. The mine severely impacted the tribe, totally disrupting their traditional patterns of life. For one thing, [[Tabubil, Papua New Guinea|Tabubil]] a town of 12,500 to house mine workers was built in the midst of their territory. Work for wages was available to tribal members, but only at the unskilled level and not on a regular basis.  The Wopkaimin along with many other ethnic groups living in the area now live on a rotating basis between the town of Tabubil, roadside villages along the [[Kiunga-Tabubil Highway]], and in villages away from the mine as jobs are lost or become available.

In 1992 a species of [[bat]], [[Bulmer's fruit bat]] (''Aproteles bulmerae'') previously thought extinct was discovered to still live in [[Luplupwintem Cave]], an enormous [[cave]] above the [[Hindenburg Wall]] in their territory. This bat was first discovered in the 1970s by David Hyndman, who studied the Wopkaimin. However the contemporaneous introduction of the [[shotgun]] was thought to have resulted in the [[extinction]] of the species.

